145
00:08:57,120 --> 00:09:00,840
Are you okay? Are you cold?

146
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:01,679
I'm okay.

147
00:09:49,639 --> 00:09:51,399
Water.

148
00:09:55,399 --> 00:09:58,799
To the challenges ahead.

149
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:03,039
Another surprising thing is how little sleep you actually need.

150
00:10:03,039 --> 00:10:05,519
I mean, I got far more sleep than Hai Guai.

151
00:10:05,519 --> 00:10:08,480
But it was still only about eight hours in total.

152
00:10:12,679 --> 00:10:15,240
Kyle, you've worked hard.

153
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:19,720
Bai Rui has a long stride.

154
00:10:20,039 --> 00:10:22,039
I have to run while he's just walking.

155
00:10:22,480 --> 00:10:23,279
Really.

156
00:10:24,320 --> 00:10:25,240
I mostly felt fine.

157
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:26,120
There was one point

158
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:29,039
when I hit some kind of limit

159
00:10:29,039 --> 00:10:30,440
from not getting enough sleep.

160
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:33,480
But after that, I managed it pretty well.

161
00:10:33,480 --> 00:10:34,080
And I realized

162
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:37,080
that sometimes an hour of sleep is enough,

163
00:10:37,080 --> 00:10:38,120
and then you can keep going.

164
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:06,039
Bai Rui and I were both exhausted.

165
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:07,320
And on that mountain,

166
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:08,960
it felt like we were just zigzagging forever.

167
00:11:10,519 --> 00:11:11,200
The switchbacks

168
00:11:11,200 --> 00:11:11,879
were gentle,

169
00:11:11,879 --> 00:11:14,960
but then we got frustrated

170
00:11:14,960 --> 00:11:16,080
and started climbing straight up.

171
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:20,879
I felt completely blown up.

172
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,759
Two three-kilometer climbs.

173
00:11:23,240 --> 00:11:24,320
The first one was hard.

174
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:25,759
The second one was even harder.

175
00:11:32,399 --> 00:11:36,240
The only times I really wanted it to end

176
00:11:36,240 --> 00:11:39,120
or really wanted to reach the next aid station

177
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:42,600
were on some of the really long downhills.

178
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:44,519
There were some downhill sections

179
00:11:44,519 --> 00:11:45,759
that were just

180
00:11:47,679 --> 00:11:49,799
painful, and I mean,

181
00:11:49,799 --> 00:11:50,279
that's why,

182
00:11:50,279 --> 00:11:52,840
my quads seized up at the end.

183
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:03,159
But other than that,

184
00:12:03,159 --> 00:12:04,720
going up the mountains,

185
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:08,519
I never really felt like I wanted it to end.

186
00:12:08,519 --> 00:12:09,440
If anything,

187
00:12:09,440 --> 00:12:10,759
I just wanted to keep going.

188
00:12:10,759 --> 00:12:13,759
Keep climbing, even on the last ascent.

189
00:12:13,759 --> 00:12:15,600
I think we were both wrecked,

190
00:12:15,600 --> 00:12:17,799
but Hai Guai still looked pretty lively.

191
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:21,639
What about at night?

192
00:12:21,679 --> 00:12:22,480
At night,

193
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:24,240
uh...

194
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:26,120
it was miserable.

195
00:12:26,799 --> 00:12:27,879
Especially on the last mountain.

196
00:12:27,879 --> 00:12:28,759
After we climbed it,

197
00:12:28,759 --> 00:12:30,200
we sat at the saddle in a daze.

198
00:12:31,639 --> 00:12:32,679
We watched the sunrise,

199
00:12:32,679 --> 00:12:34,320
and then forced ourselves to keep going.

200
00:12:35,320 --> 00:12:36,120
Uh, I...

201
00:12:36,120 --> 00:12:37,200
Honestly, the fact that

202
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:39,600
we made it this far together

203
00:12:40,039 --> 00:12:41,320
already surprised me.

204
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:44,039
Because he was still in great shape,

205
00:12:44,039 --> 00:12:46,320
and my mind was basically blank.

206
00:12:46,639 --> 00:12:47,399
I was just

207
00:12:47,399 --> 00:12:48,240
putting one foot in front of the other.

208
00:12:51,519 --> 00:12:53,080
Don't think about what's behind you.

209
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:56,120
Harder things are still waiting ahead.

210
00:12:57,600 --> 00:12:58,200
Bravo.

211
00:12:58,480 --> 00:12:59,320
Thank you.

212
00:13:02,120 --> 00:13:02,960
Thank you.

213
00:13:08,399 --> 00:13:09,919
I didn't feel like I was back on earth.

214
00:13:09,919 --> 00:13:11,759
Because I was heading back into the mountains later.

215
00:13:12,919 --> 00:13:15,879
Only getting back to Courmayeur feels like returning to earth.

216
00:13:18,679 --> 00:13:19,919
It felt so familiar,

217
00:13:20,279 --> 00:13:24,320
because it's what Hai Guai and I used to do.

218
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,679
Not for many years, of course,

219
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:29,399
I've seen Hai Guai a few times over the last few years,

220
00:13:29,399 --> 00:13:32,080
but only for fairly short runs.

221
00:13:32,080 --> 00:13:32,679
But yeah,

222
00:13:32,679 --> 00:13:34,279
three, four, five years ago,

223
00:13:34,279 --> 00:13:38,039
we did long runs together and built that connection.

224
00:13:38,039 --> 00:13:40,200
I don't quite know how to describe it,

225
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:42,240
but it's some kind of bond,

226
00:13:42,240 --> 00:13:44,320
moving forward together,

227
00:13:44,320 --> 00:13:46,120
taking on something big together.

228
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:48,320
It felt like we were right back there.

229
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:49,960
Even after three or four years

230
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:52,000
of not doing that.

231
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,840
Yeah, I mean, we talked as well,

232
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:58,200
but a lot of the time we were just moving together.

233
00:13:58,360 --> 00:14:00,480
If you're really tired when you get to Donnas,

234
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,799
you can rest there for a long time.

235
00:14:02,879 --> 00:14:05,200
I was thinking we shouldn't blow ourselves up.

236
00:14:10,120 --> 00:14:11,120
And in that rhythm,

237
00:14:11,120 --> 00:14:13,440
you develop a kind of synchronization.

238
00:14:13,440 --> 00:14:15,559
We'd want to drink water

239
00:14:15,559 --> 00:14:18,320
or eat at the same time.

240
00:14:18,320 --> 00:14:20,440
It's a fascinating connection.

241
00:14:32,960 --> 00:14:34,440
There can be long stretches of silence.

242
00:14:34,720 --> 00:14:36,919
That kind of unspoken understanding is amazing.

243
00:14:36,919 --> 00:14:38,799
Even when you don't talk,

244
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:40,440
you can still feel each other.

245
00:14:40,559 --> 00:14:41,960
Like you're doing the same thing together.

246
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:49,840
You can almost sense what the other person is thinking.

247
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:51,720
Sometimes you don't want to say anything,

248
00:14:51,720 --> 00:14:53,559
or something suddenly occurs to you.

249
00:14:53,559 --> 00:14:55,320
I've always been curious about that,

250
00:14:55,559 --> 00:14:57,519
and it just happens to be one of his strengths.

251
00:14:57,519 --> 00:14:58,440
At moments like that,

252
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,200
we talk it through.

253
00:15:03,679 --> 00:15:04,600
Time to rest.

254
00:15:04,960 --> 00:15:06,919
Yeah, let's take a nap.

255
00:15:09,679 --> 00:15:12,039
Finally, I can sleep.

256
00:15:12,120 --> 00:15:12,919
Finally.

257
00:15:12,919 --> 00:15:14,600
Oh my God.

258
00:15:16,200 --> 00:15:19,120
I've been out on the course for almost thirty hours.

259
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,279
Can we sleep now?

260
00:15:25,639 --> 00:15:26,960
I'll sleep first.

261
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:29,679
I can't hold on anymore. I'm so sleepy.

262
00:15:29,679 --> 00:15:30,360
I'm going to sleep.

263
00:15:45,759 --> 00:15:46,440
Yeah, I guess

264
00:15:46,440 --> 00:15:49,480
I kind of lost track of time,

265
00:15:49,480 --> 00:15:51,960
because I didn't have a regular sleep pattern.

266
00:15:52,720 --> 00:15:59,120
But you could still feel the rhythms of the day.

267
00:15:59,799 --> 00:16:02,759
And I guess the difference from normal life is

268
00:16:02,759 --> 00:16:05,879
that those rhythms are defined by nature,

269
00:16:05,879 --> 00:16:06,919
by the sun and the moon,

270
00:16:06,919 --> 00:16:08,759
not by the rhythms

271
00:16:08,759 --> 00:16:10,720
of human schedules and routines.

272
00:16:11,440 --> 00:16:13,799
So for me,

273
00:16:14,799 --> 00:16:15,679
in some ways,

274
00:16:15,679 --> 00:16:17,919
I preferred running at night,

275
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:21,879
because it was really peaceful.

276
00:16:21,919 --> 00:16:24,639
There were fewer people around,

277
00:16:25,240 --> 00:16:28,919
and almost less to think about.

278
00:16:28,919 --> 00:16:30,879
Because it wasn't sunny

279
00:16:30,879 --> 00:16:31,879
and it wasn't hot.

280
00:16:32,279 --> 00:16:34,000
You could just,

281
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:34,919
you just had to keep warm.

282
00:16:34,919 --> 00:16:36,120
In some places, anyway.

283
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:36,799
But that's easy.

284
00:16:36,799 --> 00:16:38,519
You just put on more layers

285
00:16:38,519 --> 00:16:39,480
and keep going.

286
00:16:39,480 --> 00:16:43,399
So I quite liked getting long sections done at night.

287
00:16:45,320 --> 00:16:47,919
And it's just easier to focus at night.

288
00:16:48,120 --> 00:16:50,320
And you also know that if you're starting to feel tired,
